@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Home Page";
}

<div class="text-center">
    <h1 class="display-4">Welcome</h1>
    <p>Learn about <a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/aspnet/core">building Web apps with ASP.NET Core</a>.</p>
</div>
<div class="text-left">
    Default ASP.NET Core 3.0 application includes three types of loggers:
    <ul>
        <li>Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.Console.ConsoleLogger</li>
        <li>Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.Debug.DebugLogger</li>
        <li>Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.EventSource.EventSourceLogger</li>
    </ul>
    Once the app starts in the container, view container logs by running one of these commands:<br/><br/>
    <div><b>docker logs {containerId}</b> - if you use Docker</div>
    <div><b>kubectl logs {POD_NAME}</b> - if you use Kubernetes</div><br/>
    You should be able to see the output generated by <b>ConsoleLogger</b> in this format:
    <br/><br/>
    <p class="text-info text-center">
        Index action of @(typeof(aspnetcore_docker_logging.Controllers.HomeController).ToString()) executed at @(DateTime.Now.ToUniversalTime())
    </p>
    Refresh the page to see a new entry in the log stream.<br/><br/>
    If you don't see the logs in the container, make sure your app has <b>Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.Console</b> NuGet package installed:<br/><br/>
    <div class="text-secondary text-center">
        dotnet add youProject.csproj package Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.Console
    </div>
</div>
